There's something down there
blocking the door!

01:41:51.450 --> 01:41:54.200
Get me out of here, Chuck.
Come on, get me out, please!

01:42:02.250 --> 01:42:04.500
Come on, Chuck. I want out.

01:42:09.350 --> 01:42:12.000
Gil, Gil, I can't move it.
You gotta push harder.

01:42:12.150 --> 01:42:14.700
Gil, push from your side! Gil!

01:42:15.150 --> 01:42:18.300
Gil, push harder from your side!

01:42:18.900 --> 01:42:21.450
Chuck! Chuck! Chuck!

01:42:21.600 --> 01:42:23.850
We gotta go, Chuck! Come on!

01:42:24.200 --> 01:42:27.350
She's going down.
Come on, Chuck! Let's go!

01:42:27.500 --> 01:42:31.000
Gil, you've gotta push from your side.

01:42:45.650 --> 01:42:48.600
No, Gil!

01:42:49.050 --> 01:42:50.850
Chuck, we've gotta go!

01:42:51.000 --> 01:42:53.600
Help me get this door!

01:43:04.400 --> 01:43:07.800
It's too late! It's going over!

01:43:08.450 --> 01:43:10.800
Skipper, it's too late!

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:13.250
- We can't stay on.
- Get off the ship!

01:43:13.450 --> 01:43:14.500
Get them in the boat!

01:43:14.600 --> 01:43:17.200
- Do it!
- All right, skipper.

01:43:34.200 --> 01:43:37.400
Oh, please!

01:45:09.000 --> 01:45:10.500
Dean!

01:46:03.500 --> 01:46:08.600
<i>Gerard, Alice, Dean, Gil.</i>

01:46:08.800 --> 01:46:11.000
<i>Today I hate the sea.</i>

01:46:11.150 --> 01:46:13.800
<i>It will never look the same again.</i>

01:46:21.200 --> 01:46:23.000
Look.

01:46:31.050 --> 01:46:34.000
Shepard.

01:47:11.000 --> 01:47:14.050
Skipper! Skipper! Skipper, look! Look!

01:47:18.050 --> 01:47:20.300
McCrea!

01:48:15.500 --> 01:48:17.000
Captain Sheldon, can you
give us a statement?

01:48:17.500 --> 01:48:20.250
What the hell went on out there?

01:48:34.950 --> 01:48:37.050
Do you have anything to say
to these parents?

01:48:37.200 --> 01:48:38.850
Yes, and it's private.

01:48:44.200 --> 01:48:47.000
- Son!
- Dad?

01:49:19.500 --> 01:49:21.300
Thought we'd find a store.

01:49:21.450 --> 01:49:25.000
Get you fixed up then...
get you something to eat.

01:49:25.750 --> 01:49:27.950
Sound good?

01:49:34.550 --> 01:49:37.550
Hey! Your size right on top. Here.

01:49:42.250 --> 01:49:45.850
Why don't you take these in the
back there and see how they fit?

01:49:48.600 --> 01:49:50.450
Ma'am, do you have boxer shorts?

01:49:50.650 --> 01:49:52.500
- Right over there, sir.
- Okay.

01:50:16.000 --> 01:50:20.000
<i>Come on! Chuck, grab my arm!
Grab my arm!</i>

01:50:26.500 --> 01:50:28.000
Chuck, you okay in there?

01:50:31.850 --> 01:50:34.200
I'm sorry.

01:50:34.400 --> 01:50:36.950
We'll be right back for the clothes.

01:50:42.800 --> 01:50:45.000
- They'll try and take his license.
- Why?

01:50:45.100 --> 01:50:47.100
'Cause they need it to be simple.

01:50:47.300 --> 01:50:48.500
They need a reason.

01:50:48.600 --> 01:50:51.100
- Who?
- All of them.

01:50:51.300 --> 01:50:53.000
Everyone on that dock.

01:50:53.100 --> 01:50:54.550
So, what are we supposed to do?

01:50:54.750 --> 01:50:56.800
Tell them what we know, the truth.

01:50:57.000 --> 01:51:00.100
- I mean, that's what he'd want.
- The truth!

01:51:01.000 --> 01:51:03.450
We went over in a squall.
What's wrong with that?

01:51:05.200 --> 01:51:07.450
Everybody knows why we went over, Tod.

01:51:07.700 --> 01:51:10.800
It wasn't from the squall.
You jibed the boat.

01:51:10.950 --> 01:51:12.600
Look, I was trying to get her upwind, all right?

01:51:12.700 --> 01:51:14.100
I mean, that's what you're supposed to do!

01:51:14.200 --> 01:51:15.650
That's not what the skipper thought.

01:51:15.850 --> 01:51:17.350
Not when you got the squares up.

01:51:17.500 --> 01:51:19.600
He was trying to spill out
the air from the main.

01:51:19.750 --> 01:51:21.400
It was coming four poonts off the bow, Tracy.

01:51:21.600 --> 01:51:22.700
It never would've gotten--

01:51:22.850 --> 01:51:23.900
Were you on the deck?!

01:51:24.000 --> 01:51:25.650
Because I was standing right there!

01:51:25.800 --> 01:51:27.800
And all I know is that Tod
disobeyed an order twice!

01:51:27.950 --> 01:51:28.900
Look, it didn't--

01:51:29.000 --> 01:51:30.000
That's when the boat went over.

01:51:30.100 --> 01:51:32.000
It didn't go over until I turned her port!

01:51:32.200 --> 01:51:34.700
Man, you're all missing the point, anyway.

01:51:34.850 --> 01:51:36.500
This is because of Frank.

01:51:36.700 --> 01:51:38.100
Frank and dear old dad.

01:51:38.200 --> 01:51:39.650
What are you talking about?

01:51:39.800 --> 01:51:44.200
I'm talking about, they're here,
staying at the damn Rhett House.

01:51:44.300 --> 01:51:46.100
I mean, how do you think
this thing got put together so fast?

01:51:46.200 --> 01:51:49.350
The old man's been out
for skipper since day one.

01:51:49.550 --> 01:51:51.700
The skipper booted his kid off the boat!

01:51:51.800 --> 01:51:53.300
What did you expect?

01:51:53.450 --> 01:51:56.300
I told you he was a turncoat
the day we kicked him off, man.

01:51:57.500 --> 01:51:59.100
Damn kid!

01:52:22.900 --> 01:52:25.000
Frank?

01:52:27.800 --> 01:52:28.800
Frank!

01:52:28.900 --> 01:52:30.200
Can we talk?

01:52:33.050 --> 01:52:35.000
Yeah, I guess.

01:52:36.100 --> 01:52:37.200
What are you doing here?

01:52:37.300 --> 01:52:39.200
Frank, who are you talking to?

01:52:39.400 --> 01:52:42.050
Yeah, it's all right. I'll be in in a minute.

01:52:44.300 --> 01:52:46.000
What do you want?

01:52:46.800 --> 01:52:49.200
Everyone's saying that...

01:52:49.700 --> 01:52:53.450
that this whole tribunal is happening
because of your old man.

01:52:53.650 --> 01:52:55.150
And because of you.

01:52:55.300 --> 01:52:57.000
Is that true?

01:52:57.150 --> 01:52:58.600
It's just typical, isn't it?

01:52:58.750 --> 01:53:01.500
- Well, is it true, Frank?
- I gotta go.

01:53:01.600 --> 01:53:04.300
Frank, he was not out on that ship!

01:53:04.450 --> 01:53:06.800
And he doesn't know what happened.
Frank, you don't know what happened!

01:53:06.950 --> 01:53:11.000
- I know enough!
- Frank, please!

01:53:12.600 --> 01:53:15.250
Frank, get him to call it off.

01:53:18.200 --> 01:53:20.450
I'm sorry.

01:53:22.150 --> 01:53:24.000
Wait.

01:53:28.000 --> 01:53:30.000
What is this?

01:53:30.850 --> 01:53:33.250
You do what you've gotta do, Frank.

01:53:36.800 --> 01:53:39.000
The United States Coast Guard

01:53:39.200 --> 01:53:42.200
has been asked to conduct
this maritime hearing

01:53:42.400 --> 01:53:46.900
to consider the revocation
of captain Christopher Sheldon's

01:53:47.000 --> 01:53:49.300
U.S. master seaman's certificate.

01:53:50.800 --> 01:53:53.450
All right, captain Sanders, you may begin.

01:53:59.050 --> 01:54:01.500
The Albatross.

01:54:01.650 --> 01:54:04.750
By all accounts, a sound vessel.

01:54:05.500 --> 01:54:09.700
An experienced captain, an able crew.

01:54:09.850 --> 01:54:13.400
And yet it lies out there on the bottom

01:54:13.550 --> 01:54:16.750
in 2,000 fathoms with its back broken.

01:54:17.700 --> 01:54:22.100
There are serious questions that
demand our most serious consideration,

01:54:22.250 --> 01:54:25.500
so that we might understand,
so that perhaps

01:54:25.700 --> 01:54:30.000
we may prevent such a sad event
from ever taking place again.

01:54:31.000 --> 01:54:33.100
A freak accident?

01:54:33.300 --> 01:54:37.050
A one in a million meteorological anomaly?

01:54:37.200 --> 01:54:42.000
Or was it inexperience? Misjudgment?

01:54:42.400 --> 01:54:46.100
Negligence? We'll see.

01:54:53.200 --> 01:54:55.000
Please.

01:55:06.200 --> 01:55:08.000
- Thank you.
- Captain, Sheldon...

01:55:08.500 --> 01:55:11.100
Captain Sheldon, would you consider
yourself a good judge of character

01:55:11.300 --> 01:55:12.450
when it came to the boys?

01:55:12.600 --> 01:55:13.700
Yes.

01:55:14.000 --> 01:55:15.700
And it would be important,
would it not, in your position

01:55:15.800 --> 01:55:18.150
to have some sense of their
strengths and weaknesses?

01:55:18.350 --> 01:55:19.750
Yes, of course.

01:55:19.900 --> 01:55:23.900
Do you recall an incident
involving Gil Martin?

01:55:24.800 --> 01:55:26.750
What incident would you be referring to?

01:55:26.900 --> 01:55:30.100
Well, is it true that you forced
Gil Martin to climb the mast

01:55:30.250 --> 01:55:33.100
when it was clear that he was acrophobic?

01:55:33.250 --> 01:55:35.250
He climbed when he was ready.

01:55:35.450 --> 01:55:38.450
Were you aware that
his brother was killed in a fall?

01:55:38.650 --> 01:55:40.300
Yes, I was.

01:55:40.500 --> 01:55:43.600
sir, were you aware at any time
of the use of alcohol among your crew?

01:55:43.700 --> 01:55:44.950
Yes, I was.

01:55:45.100 --> 01:55:47.600
- You didn't do anything about it?
- No, I did not.

01:55:47.750 --> 01:55:51.050
Had you ever seen a white squall
before this incident?

01:55:51.700 --> 01:55:53.100
No.

01:55:53.300 --> 01:55:56.200
And what makes you so sure it was one?

01:55:56.700 --> 01:55:58.850
I can't be sure.

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:02.000
You really felt that your crew
was up to the conditions?

01:56:02.450 --> 01:56:07.000
we had come 12,000 miles together
through every kind of seas imaginable.

01:56:07.200 --> 01:56:08.900
Except a white squall.

01:56:09.000 --> 01:56:11.650
Now, with all due respect,
captain, they're only boys.

01:56:14.800 --> 01:56:17.800
They're much more than that, sir.

01:56:18.450 --> 01:56:20.700
ls it true the reason
you expelled Frank Beaumont--

01:56:20.900 --> 01:56:23.200
For killing a dolphin.

01:56:23.800 --> 01:56:25.800
And that you invited him to strike you,

01:56:25.900 --> 01:56:28.700
to fight it out on the deck of the ship?

01:56:32.900 --> 01:56:34.850
Yes, that is true.

01:56:35.050 --> 01:56:38.600
So, you allowed the use of alcohol,
among other things, to go unpunished

01:56:38.800 --> 01:56:43.100
and yet you expelled this boy
for killing a fish.

01:56:43.300 --> 01:56:46.450
- A mammal.
- A mammal.

01:56:50.150 --> 01:56:51.900
It would appear to me sir,
with all due respect,

01:56:52.100 --> 01:56:55.350
that your stewardship
as captain of the Albatross

01:56:55.500 --> 01:56:59.600
could be characterized
as reckless, unbalanced,

01:56:59.700 --> 01:57:02.700
with no discipline whatsoever.

01:57:04.500 --> 01:57:06.000
Do you find this funny?

01:57:08.400 --> 01:57:10.000
Some kind of joke?

01:57:11.000 --> 01:57:15.050
I don't think one second of this is funny, sir.

01:57:17.050 --> 01:57:18.850
The national weather service
says white squalls

01:57:19.050 --> 01:57:21.550
are a meteorological phenomenon
of the imaglnation.

01:57:21.700 --> 01:57:23.200
What do you say to that?

01:57:23.300 --> 01:57:26.050
What happened to my ship
was not imagined.

01:57:26.200 --> 01:57:29.050
It was not a dream, sir.

01:57:29.300 --> 01:57:32.000
No, captain Sheldon, it was not.

01:57:33.100 --> 01:57:35.300
It was a nightmare.

01:57:37.700 --> 01:57:40.200
Now, Shay, I need you to help me out.

01:57:40.400 --> 01:57:42.800
On the day of the accident,

01:57:42.950 --> 01:57:46.500
do you remember where you were
when the lightning first struck?

01:57:47.400 --> 01:57:51.100
I was on deck. Midships.

01:57:52.050 --> 01:57:56.650
During this squall that ensued,

01:57:57.000 --> 01:57:59.050
why didn't you drop any sail?

01:57:59.200 --> 01:58:01.500
Skipper called us out of the rigging.

01:58:01.650 --> 01:58:05.350
But your instinct was to lose sail?

01:58:05.550 --> 01:58:09.900
Skipper's instinct was to not
get any any of us electrocuted.

01:58:16.150 --> 01:58:18.000
How old are you, son?

01:58:19.700 --> 01:58:21.450
15.

01:58:25.200 --> 01:58:27.650
And you were the first mate
of the Albatross, is that correct?

01:58:27.800 --> 01:58:30.750
I am the first mate of the Albatross.
That's correct.

01:58:32.500 --> 01:58:35.400
And are you a professional sailor, son?

01:58:41.250 --> 01:58:43.750
No, I'm not a professional sailor.

01:58:50.800 --> 01:58:54.050
You say you turned hard to
starboard when the gust hit.

01:58:54.200 --> 01:58:56.850
I thought we'd have a better chance,
if I headed into the wind.

01:58:57.000 --> 01:58:59.500
But the captain ordered you hard to port.

01:59:00.050 --> 01:59:01.400
- Twice.
- I'm sorry?

01:59:01.500 --> 01:59:03.000
Twice!

01:59:03.300 --> 01:59:05.450
Is that what you were trained to do?

01:59:06.500 --> 01:59:07.900
No.

01:59:08.000 --> 01:59:09.200
Speak up, son. I can't hear you.

01:59:09.300 --> 01:59:10.400
I said no.

01:59:10.500 --> 01:59:13.000
And what did you think he was trying to do?

01:59:13.550 --> 01:59:15.650
Put her off.

01:59:15.800 --> 01:59:17.600
To let the blow drive the boat downwind.

01:59:17.700 --> 01:59:19.600
By the "blow" you're referring
to the force of the storm, is that right?

01:59:19.700 --> 01:59:22.200
Let the blow drive the boat downwind,

01:59:22.350 --> 01:59:24.050
and neutralize our canvas.

01:59:24.200 --> 01:59:26.900
So when the captain gave you
an order contrary to your training,

01:59:27.000 --> 01:59:29.500
you thought he was making a mistake.

01:59:31.750 --> 01:59:33.000
No.

01:59:33.150 --> 01:59:35.350
Then why son?

01:59:35.500 --> 01:59:38.050
Why didn't you follow his order?

01:59:38.450 --> 01:59:40.650
Because...

01:59:43.700 --> 01:59:45.100
I panicked.

01:59:45.200 --> 01:59:47.700
You know that's not true, Tod!

01:59:52.200 --> 01:59:54.000
Do you believe he panicked?

01:59:54.500 --> 01:59:56.000
What the hell is he doing?

01:59:56.350 --> 01:59:57.950
Quiet, please.

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:02.750
Maybe you can't see what's
happening here, but I can.

02:00:04.250 --> 02:00:06.450
Tod, I appreciate what
you're trying to do here.

02:00:06.600 --> 02:00:09.350
Maybe you could live with it, but I couldn't.

02:00:10.000 --> 02:00:12.150
lf you think I'm gonna let
a 17-year-old take responsibility,

02:00:12.250 --> 02:00:14.150
then you underestimate me.

02:00:14.350 --> 02:00:18.850
The Albatross was my ship.
The Ocean Academy was my school.

02:00:19.000 --> 02:00:22.150
Her responsibility is mine and mine alone.

02:00:32.450 --> 02:00:36.000
I can't bring your sons back.

02:00:37.300 --> 02:00:41.800
If you want my ticket,
if that will ease your pain,

02:00:42.750 --> 02:00:45.800
that's the least that I can do.

02:00:55.600 --> 02:00:58.600
- This, this is easy.
- Captain sheldon!

02:01:00.200 --> 02:01:01.950
- Captain!
- No.

02:01:02.150 --> 02:01:04.000
- Order, please, order.
- This proceeding is not over, captain.

02:01:04.100 --> 02:01:07.000
- I still have further questions for this witness.
- No.

02:01:07.200 --> 02:01:08.500
Order!

02:01:08.800 --> 02:01:11.300
Don't you walk out on us, skipper! You don't!

02:01:15.500 --> 02:01:18.000
You tell me, was it all just a lie?

02:01:18.300 --> 02:01:21.000
Was it? Because we listened
to you, we believed you!

02:01:21.200 --> 02:01:23.300
And we are still here!

02:01:24.850 --> 02:01:26.800
Bad things happen sometimes,

02:01:26.900 --> 02:01:29.000
and there's nothing
that you can do about it.

02:01:29.100 --> 02:01:33.050
It wasn't you. Or Tod. It wasn't you, Tod.

02:01:33.650 --> 02:01:36.750
It was all of us, everyone in this room.

02:01:36.900 --> 02:01:40.300
Because we all knew the risks
we were taking going out there.

02:01:40.400 --> 02:01:43.400
You paid our tuition, and you told us to go.

02:01:43.550 --> 02:01:47.000
So, why do we just have to invent
some reason now for why this happened?

02:01:47.100 --> 02:01:49.000
Just pin it on one person?

02:01:50.300 --> 02:01:51.700
Why?

02:01:55.500 --> 02:01:58.750
Then shame on you, skipper. Shame on you!

02:01:59.300 --> 02:02:02.000
Mr. Gieg.

02:02:05.000 --> 02:02:08.300
I was in command of the Albatross.

02:02:08.450 --> 02:02:11.400
And I was responsible for precious cargo.

02:02:13.250 --> 02:02:16.400
It was my job to get you all home safely

02:02:16.500 --> 02:02:18.000
with my knowledge and my skill.

02:02:18.150 --> 02:02:21.300
That's the contract that I made
with your parents.

02:02:21.400 --> 02:02:24.400
But something happened out there.
I lost control.

02:02:25.600 --> 02:02:29.650
Maybe just for an instant.
Maybe all along. I'm not sure.

02:02:29.850 --> 02:02:32.850
But I know this. I never saw it coming.

02:02:33.000 --> 02:02:37.350
It was like I just woke up,
and a hand came down

02:02:37.500 --> 02:02:40.700
and pushed my sails into the sea.

02:02:40.850 --> 02:02:43.700
It got away for me, the whole thing.

02:02:45.200 --> 02:02:47.900
And people died.

02:02:50.700 --> 02:02:55.000
Now, you're young and strong.

02:02:56.400 --> 02:02:58.000
Everything's ahead of you.

02:02:58.550 --> 02:03:00.600
You told us, "where we go one, we go all."

02:03:00.750 --> 02:03:05.050
Well, we believed you. We lived by it, sir.

02:03:05.200 --> 02:03:09.000
And now you're saying that
where you go, we can't follow.

02:03:10.050 --> 02:03:11.700
Mr. Gieg.

02:03:11.900 --> 02:03:17.950
The Albatross wasn't just a ship or a school.

02:03:19.300 --> 02:03:21.200
It was something that we made.

02:03:23.000 --> 02:03:24.750
Something that's inside of us.

02:03:27.450 --> 02:03:29.300
That's who you are, skipper.

02:03:29.500 --> 02:03:32.900
What you gave us. You carried us.

02:03:33.050 --> 02:03:37.700
Now, let us carry this together.
Let us carry this together.

02:03:38.750 --> 02:03:42.350
Let it go. Just go home.

02:04:57.600 --> 02:05:00.050
<i>They didn't take his ticket today.</i>

02:05:00.200 --> 02:05:03.150
<i>But I wonder if he'll ever go to sea again.</i>

02:05:03.350 --> 02:05:04.500
<i>I know one thing.</i>

02:05:04.650 --> 02:05:06.950
<i>If he did, we'd all go with him.</i>

02:05:07.100 --> 02:05:10.650
<i>To a man. No doubt. Not even a question.</i>

02:05:10.850 --> 02:05:15.000
<i>Today he joined the circle he created
by allowing us to share his burden.</i>

02:05:15.700 --> 02:05:19.500
<i>The burden of sea captains and fathers,</i>

02:05:19.700 --> 02:05:21.600
<i>the burden of men.</i>

02:05:21.750 --> 02:05:24.350
<i>In the end, it just comes down to one thing.</i>

02:05:24.500 --> 02:05:26.300
<i>You can't run from the wind.</i>

02:05:26.500 --> 02:05:30.700
<i>You face the music, you trim
your sails, and keep going.</i>

02:05:30.850 --> 02:05:38.500
♪ She's the dark star over the sea ♪

02:05:39.400 --> 02:05:46.750
♪ Go where my true love is waiting for me ♪

02:05:48.100 --> 02:05:55.800
♪ Rode the south wind,
canvas the stars ♪

02:05:56.850 --> 02:06:03.950
♪ Harness the moonlight,
so she can safely go ♪

